# QA Standard (BINDING)

This repo is governed by the **HDPulseAI QA Standard** at
[docs/qa/STANDARD.md](mdc:docs/qa/STANDARD.md). The per-PR checklist is
[docs/qa/definition-of-done.md](mdc:docs/qa/definition-of-done.md). Both apply
to every change you produce in this repo.

## You MUST, on every code change

- Add or update at least one spec under the relevant pillar folder
  (`tests/e2e/<smoke|rbac|phi-scope|flows|a11y|visual|responsive|security|
  contract|external|time|concurrency|files|compliance|observability|live-stack>/**`,
  `tests/contract/**`, `tests/perf/**`, `tests/security/**`, `tests/data/**`,
  `tests/observability/**`, or `tests/docs/**`). Pillars are listed in
  `docs/qa/STANDARD.md` §2 (A–S, version 1.2.0+). **Pillar S — Live-Stack
  Reality Gate** (added 2026-04-19, [ADR 0028](mdc:docs/dev/adr/0028-live-stack-reality-gate.md))
  is REQUIRED for every PR that touches `src/server/auth.ts`,
  `src/middleware.ts`, `prisma/**`, `Dockerfile.*`, `docker-compose.*.yml`,
  `.env*`, `scripts/web-entrypoint.sh`, `src/lib/api/error-catalog.ts`, or
  any `src/app/api/auth/**` route.
- Run `npm run qa:inventory` if you added a route, link, REST endpoint, tRPC
  procedure, bot, webhook, scheduled job, or form. Commit the regenerated
  inventories under `docs/qa/inventories/`.
- Add a per-screen card at `docs/qa/per-screen/<slug>.md` for any new route,
  with `Linked specs:` populated.
- Add a per-flow card at `docs/qa/per-flow/<slug>.md` for any new user flow,
  with `Linked specs:` populated.
- Keep `scripts/qa/check-coverage.ts` green.

## You MUST treat as HARD FAILURES (never warnings)

1. Any browser console `error`.
2. Any React hydration warning
   (`Expected server HTML to contain a matching …`).
3. Any uncaught `TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'call')`
   or other unhandled exception.
4. Any 5xx from a first-party route, tRPC procedure, or webhook.
5. Any axe-core `serious`/`critical` violation on a touched route.
6. Any PHI field appearing in a response served to a role that should not see
   it (Operations, RCM/Billing, providers viewing other providers, public API).
7. **(STANDARD.md §4 (11), added 1.2.0)** Any pending Prisma migration or
   schema drift against the deployed database
   (`npm run qa:migrations` red).
8. **(STANDARD.md §4 (12), added 1.2.0)** Any seeded staff role failing
   the live CSRF + `/api/auth/callback/credentials` round-trip on the
   deployed stack (`npm run qa:live-stack` red).
9. **(STANDARD.md §4 (13), added 1.2.0)** Any cold Dockerfile rebuild
   failure across any compose file
   (`npm run qa:dockerfile -- --cold` red).
10. **(STANDARD.md §4 (14), added 1.2.0)** Stale named-volume contents
    shadowing the deployed image (Pillar S `--volume-probe` red).

## You MUST report results using the headline block (coverage FIRST)

```
Routes covered:    X of Y
Roles exercised:   X of N
Pillars touched:   <A–S IDs>
Pillars green:     <A–S IDs>
Pillars not run:   <A–S IDs>      (must be empty for release)
Live stack:        <commit SHA running in container> | migrations: 0 pending | sign-in matrix: ADMIN/MANAGER/SPECIALIST/COMMITTEE_MEMBER all green
Pass / Fail / Skip: P / F / S
```

A pass/fail count without coverage is **not** a valid report. Any "Not Run"
entry for a covered pillar counts as a **fail** of the gate, not a pass. The
legacy report shape `Pass: 33, Fail: 0, Not Run: 223` is explicitly forbidden
(see `STANDARD.md` §10.1). The newer "all green static gates while sign-in
is broken on the deployed stack" report shape is also forbidden (see
`STANDARD.md` §10.2 / DEF-0009 / ADR 0028) — every release report MUST
include the `Live stack:` line and that line MUST reflect a real
`npm run qa:live-stack` run, not a hand-edit.

## You MUST NOT

- Mark a feature "tested" without BOTH automation AND a per-screen/per-flow
  card with `Linked specs:` populated.
- Fall back to an HTTP-only probe (e.g. `docs/testing/run_master_test_plan.py`)
  and call the result "passing" when the browser layer would have caught the
  issue.
- Add a mutation that bypasses `writeAuditLog`.
- Return PHI to the public API or to roles that should not see it.

## Fix-Until-Green loop (BINDING — STANDARD.md §4.1)

If any spec fails or any §4 hard-fail condition fires, you MUST:

1. **Capture** evidence: spec name + path, console error, stack trace,
   `trace.zip`, screenshot, video, network HAR for any 5xx, browser, role,
   route at time of fail.
2. **File a defect card** at [docs/qa/defects/DEF-####.md](mdc:docs/qa/defects)
   using [the template](mdc:docs/qa/defects/_TEMPLATE.md).
3. **Diagnose root cause.** Fix priority: (a) production code →
   (b) genuinely-wrong assertion → (c) flaky fixture. Never weaken.
4. **Apply minimum fix.** One root cause per commit. Update the DEF card.
5. **Re-run the FULL pillar**, not just the single spec. Smoke (A) re-runs
   on every fix regardless. Cross-cutting fixes re-run every pillar that
   exercises the touched layer.
6. **Loop** until green OR 3 attempts on the same root cause have failed.

**Attempt cap: N=3 per root cause.** After 3 unsuccessful attempts: STOP,
update the DEF card with every attempt + output, escalate to the user with
the evidence, and do **not** mark the work done.

## Anti-weakening (BINDING — STANDARD.md §4.2)

A red spec MUST NOT be turned green by:

- Weakening assertions (`toBe` → `toBeTruthy`, etc.).
- Deleting / renaming out of glob / `.skip` / `.todo` / `.fixme` / `xtest` /
  `xit` / `describe.skip`.
- Widening selectors (`locator('a')`, `getByRole('button')` without name).
- Swallowing errors (`try { } catch {}`, `.catch(() => {})`, `expect.soft`,
  `test.fail`).
- Silencing with `@ts-expect-error` or `eslint-disable-next-line`.
- Mocking the failing path without proving the mock matches production.
- Raising timeouts to mask races.
- Softening strict equality to substring / regex match.
- Lowering coverage thresholds in any pillar config.
- Editing `scripts/qa/check-coverage.ts` or inventories to silence a
  complaint.

Each is, by itself, a violation and grounds for revert. Legitimate fixes:
(1) fix the production code, (2) fix a genuinely-wrong assertion (cite doc
in DEF card), (3) fix a flaky fixture (3 consecutive green runs in DEF card).

